That’s it! It’s so simple that it made me go buy another sad-looking African violet marked on clearance at a local nursery and bring it back to life.

With its versatility, ease of use, and cost-effectiveness, CALiMAGic proves to be an invaluable asset for maximizing yields and achieving successful indoor cannabis cultivation.

Review text: Would give 10 stars but with a small disclaimer. I’ve used it on my many, many pothos plants, specifically to regrow some patches that were bare from leaves falling off, and I’ve had great luck. Almost every single node would grow a new leaf, and I’ve been able to fill in most of the bare spots almost entirely. I’ve also used it on a fig tree that I brought indoors and have had amazing results, many new places of growth, even where there were not previously any branches. That being said, it is quite sticky and a bit smelly and is somewhat challenging to get off. Even after washing your hands with soap, the smell remains AND I’ve had stickiness remain. Using the q-tip like applicator isn’t super easy, so application can be a bit tricky, but once it is on, it’s amazing. Using the q-tip like applicator seems to leave lots of product on your fingers, hence the stickiness when applying. It is also something that doesn’t dry out and seemingly stays on the nodes forever (or at least several months as far as I can tell), so it is best to use it on plants that you are not planning on handling right away or that are in a permanent spot.

Review text: I was kind of skeptical about if this would actually work, especially for my jade plants, and I was overjoyed to find out that it does!, Had an unfortunate grow light accident when a bunch of leaves got burned and fell off and bought this as a last resort for saving them. Followed the instructions for lightly scratching the node and dabbing on a bit of paste, and after a few weeks new sprouts started growing! I’m so excited, I think my jades will look better than ever once the new branches grow in fully, because it will be a whole new branch, not just a leaf. It’s like the results you get from pruning, no cutting required! I even used this stuff on a node with two totally intact leaves, and a new sprout started growing!, Like I mentioned, I also use grow lights I bought here (Gooingtop Grow Light 100w) which I think help a lot with the quick growth (just make sure no one accidentally moves them too close to avoid burns!) so I suggest using them in together. I also use Miracle Grow cactus and succulent fertilizer about once a month, which may also help., Amazing stuff, will definitely keep using it. I like that they include Q-tips to apply it. You really don’t need a lot, I actually found that too much slows down growth a bit, so I don’t mind that the bottle is very small. I’ve used probably about a quarter of the container on multiple nodes on five plants. Smells a bit like lanolin, but it’s not terrible or very strong and doesn’t linger after application., I definitely recommend this, and will be using it for as long as I have jade plants.

Review text:
Using the q-tip like applicator isn’t super easy, so application can be a bit tricky, but once it is on, it’s amazing.

Using the q-tip like applicator seems to leave lots of product on your fingers, hence the stickiness when applying.

It is also something that doesn’t dry out and seemingly stays on the nodes forever (or at least several months as far as I can tell), so it is best to use it on plants that you are not planning on handling right away or that are in a permanent spot.

Review text: I’m new to plants. I got this awesome potted mandevilla with a tropical leaf plant from the hardware garden center year and loved it, bloomed all summer with no effort but water and deadheading that neighbor showed me. This year I got the same one, except it hasn’t bloomed since I picked up in May with the blooms she had. I added some eco nitrogen fertilizer because last year I learned and saw how many of my plants loved nitrogen… but alas I did not know it was just gonna make her grow long and green…. Like my grass and greens that loved it haha! Anyway. After looking up online how to make it bloom (and that I made her not bloom with the nitrogen lol), I deduced she needed phosphorus since she has plenty of sun and watered as directed. I got this product on Wednesday. I chose this one because I loved the ingredient list (yes for bug casings!) - I’m very into sustainability and I only use organic and natural gardening products along with compost. I watered the mandevillas with the directions in the evening. It is Saturday morning and I’m already seeing little blooms instead of new baby leaves forming finally!!! Literally in 48 hours she was stimulated enough to grow them overnight., I also picked up a red climbing mandevilla last weekend from the clearance section. Then bottom stilled looked green and healthy, the top was veryyy sad, but I think it was only half off cuz the plastic display pot was cracked judging by the full price ones. Figured it was worth a shot for a cheap price. She had a few flowers, and I added another pole to help it climb since the top was the very sad part. I put this on it also on Wednesday night and holy cow!! It’s like I got a very healthy plant from the store, and has popped out TONS of tiny little flowers to bloom since yesterday! I also added her to these stupid daisies in the ground that wilted out pretty fast and has only put out tiny blooms, and I noticed I have a flower blooming and little round pods trying to form, but not as drastically as the photos of the mandevilla I posted here.

Review text: I’m new to plants. I got this awesome potted mandevilla with a tropical leaf plant from the hardware garden center year and loved it, bloomed all summer with no effort but water and deadheading that neighbor showed me. This year I got the same one, except it hasn’t bloomed since I picked up in May with the blooms she had. Review text: This powder dusted on the ends of stems of cuttings promotes the formation on new "adventitious" roots., "I tried it on a Coleus cutting, and after about 5 days there were visible new root buds (primordia) popping out of the base of the stem.  I did not try a control experiment with a cutting to which no powder was added (probably would also have formed roots, but not so quickly).  At first, I dusted the roots with this powder and put the cutting into a small shot glass with water in it. Change the water every 3 days or so, or it may get fungus on it!  Keep the cutting in subdued light. Trim off lower leaves, leaving the shoot to grow. The Coleus cutting is now planted in soil and growing pretty fast.  Very good for propagating cuttings, perhaps even from more rare plants. I think its worth buying."

Review text: I wish I had a better "Before" photo to show the difference because the photo I used is not my lawn when it was at its worst.  That is the photo from when the house was up for sale.  After I bought it, I went through years of just completely ignoring my lawn while I was going through some medical problems and could not deal with yard care. Of course after that, anything that grew in that spot just ended up being more weeds (mostly crabgrass, dandelions, etc).  It was a terrible eyesore and embarrassment to me.  After my health problems resolved, I started taking more pride in my house appearance again. My mom had been pushing me to use Turf Builder for years because it had dramatic results for her.  I didn't really believe her so I sometimes procrastinated. I started to use this product more, along with overseeding on my own, more religiously every season.  These are the results of just 1.5 years of growth.  My lawn went from one of the worst looking in the neighborhood to one of the best.  The grass is full and lush.  I can start taking pride in the outward appearance of my home again. Review text: I planted 8 San Marzano plants this spring that I grew from seed and then transferred to Garden Patch brand Grow Pots. Once the tomatoes began to set fruit it was immediately evident that blossom end rot was going to be an issue. San Marzanos are know to have issues with this and other calcium supplements have helped with this in past years, so since I was using bottom watering pots I decided to give this product a try since it is a liquid and there is literature online about its use in hydroponic and hybrid hydroponic gardening. It was easy to use as I added the recommended amount directly to the water tank each time I filled it and adjusted the pH accordingly. Initially it seemed to be working great but it only lasted a few weeks before the BER came back severely enough that even with daily use of CalMag I ended up having to remove the plants early due to lack of usable production. I soil tested regularly and everything looked ok and all of my other tomato varieties had a bumper crop this year. So with all that being said I was probably hoping for more than this product was really capable of delivering with problematic San Marzano’s but I was hoping to at least get one batch of usable tomatoes for sauce which did not happen.

Review text: I planted 8 San Marzano plants this spring that I grew from seed and then transferred to Garden Patch brand Grow Pots. Once the tomatoes began to set fruit it was immediately evident that blossom end rot was going to be an issue. San Marzanos are know to have issues with this and other calcium supplements have helped with this in past years, so since I was using bottom watering pots I decided to give this product a try since it is a liquid and there is literature online about its use in hydroponic and hybrid hydroponic gardening. It was easy to use as I added the recommended amount directly to the water tank each time I filled it and adjusted the pH accordingly. Initially it seemed to be working great but it only lasted a few weeks before the BER came back severely enough that even with daily use of CalMag I ended up having to remove the plants early due to lack of usable production. I soil tested regularly and everything looked ok and all of my other tomato varieties had a bumper crop this year. So with all that being said I was probably hoping for more than this product was really capable of delivering with problematic San Marzano’s but I was hoping to at least get one batch of usable tomatoes for sauce which did not happen.

Review text: I have been growing most of our veggies and herbs in our basement for about 6 years, and have had great success with this endeavor. I often grow more produce than we can use and give the excess to a local food pantry., I started using this fertilizer a couple of months ago on new plants by mixing 1/4 cup per 5 gallons of soil. The result I am seeing are amazing. My zucchini and yellow squash plants are larger and healthier than they have in previous grows, and are producing more flowers. The same is true for my bush tomato plants. My previous grow of bush tomatoes was good and they produced well, but they never got as large as my current tomato plants, nor did they produce as many tomatoes without blossom rot., There is a reason for this increased success. The potting soils used for indoor growing are usually sterilized to kill unwanted pests and possible fungal diseases, but this also kills the good microbes and organisms that are beneficial to growing plants., This fertilizer adds the seven strains of beneficial soil microbes plus ecto and endo mycorrhizae which are fungi that have a symbiotic relationship with the plants.. . Ectomycorrhizae do not penetrate deep into the plant (the cortical cells), while endo mycorrhizae tend to penetrate deeper (into the cortical cells). Endomycorrhizae literally attach themselves to the roots, penetrate cell walls, and become one with the roots. Endomycorrhizae form symbiotic relationships with 80 to 90 percent of all plants, including turf. On the other hand, ectomycorrhizae just kind of lay up next to the roots, coming into very close proximity but don’t attach themselves. Mycorrhizae are responsible for increasing the uptake of nutrients, minerals, and moisture by the plant  The plant and mycorrhizae form a mutualistic relationship whereby the plant produces sugars through photosynthesis and exudes them out of the roots for mycorrhizae and other beneficial microorganisms to consume. For plants, the big benefit is the “enhanced supply of available nutrients, including carbon, potassium, phosphorus and nitrogen. They also get a faster uptake of minerals, such as calcium, copper, iron and zinc, and in greater amounts than would normally have been available to their roots.” As a result, mycorrhizae allows for an increased tolerance to adverse soil conditions (think low amounts of NPK and poor pH)., What this all means is that this fertilizer helps to supply beneficial organisms found naturally in outdoor soil but does not exist in the potting soil used for plants grown indoors. In my experience, this fertilizer has definitely increased the growth and production of the many plants that I grow., Although I believe this fertilizer would be beneficial for growing indoors or outdoors, it will not compensate for under or over watering.. You need to know the needs of the plants you are growing., I hope this review was helpful for you.

Review text: I have been growing most of our veggies and herbs in our basement for about 6 years, and have had great success with this endeavor. I often grow more produce than we can use and give the excess to a local food pantry., I started using this fertilizer a couple of months ago on new plants by mixing 1/4 cup per 5 gallons of soil. The result I am seeing are amazing. My zucchini and yellow squash plants are larger and healthier than they have in previous grows, and are producing more flowers. The same is true for my bush tomato plants. My previous grow of bush tomatoes was good and they produced well, but they never got as large as my current tomato plants, nor did they produce as many tomatoes without blossom rot., There is a reason for this increased success. The potting soils used for indoor growing are usually sterilized to kill unwanted pests and possible fungal diseases, but this also kills the good microbes and organisms that are beneficial to growing plants., This fertilizer adds the seven strains of beneficial soil microbes plus ecto and endo mycorrhizae which are fungi that have a symbiotic relationship with the plants.. . Ectomycorrhizae do not penetrate deep into the plant (the cortical cells), while endo mycorrhizae tend to penetrate deeper (into the cortical cells). Endomycorrhizae literally attach themselves to the roots, penetrate cell walls, and become one with the roots. Endomycorrhizae form symbiotic relationships with 80 to 90 percent of all plants, including turf. On the other hand, ectomycorrhizae just kind of lay up next to the roots, coming into very close proximity but don’t attach themselves. Mycorrhizae are responsible for increasing the uptake of nutrients, minerals, and moisture by the plant  The plant and mycorrhizae form a mutualistic relationship whereby the plant produces sugars through photosynthesis and exudes them out of the roots for mycorrhizae and other beneficial microorganisms to consume. For plants, the big benefit is the “enhanced supply of available nutrients, including carbon, potassium, phosphorus and nitrogen. They also get a faster uptake of minerals, such as calcium, copper, iron and zinc, and in greater amounts than would normally have been available to their roots.” As a result, mycorrhizae allows for an increased tolerance to adverse soil conditions (think low amounts of NPK and poor pH)., What this all means is that this fertilizer helps to supply beneficial organisms found naturally in outdoor soil but does not exist in the potting soil used for plants grown indoors. In my experience, this fertilizer has definitely increased the growth and production of the many plants that I grow., Although I believe this fertilizer would be beneficial for growing indoors or outdoors, it will not compensate for under or over watering.. You need to know the needs of the plants you are growing., I hope this review was helpful for you.

Review text: "As an avid gardener and lover of evergreen trees, I have tried numerous fertilizers over the years, but none have impressed me as much as Jobes Fertilizer Spikes. These specially designed spikes are a game-changer when it comes to nourishing and maintaining the health of my cypress, juniper, and magnolia trees. From their slow release formula to the ease of use, Jobes Fertilizer Spikes have exceeded my expectations on every front.", "The first thing that caught my attention was the innovative slow release formula. Unlike other fertilizers that provide a quick burst of nutrients, Jobes Fertilizer Spikes deliver a consistent and steady release of essential elements over an extended period. This slow release approach ensures that my evergreen trees receive a continuous supply of nutrients, promoting healthy growth and vibrant foliage. Its a hands-off solution that saves me time and effort, as I dont have to worry about frequent applications.", "What sets Jobes Fertilizer Spikes apart from other options is their convenience and ease of use. Each spike is pre-measured with the ideal amount of nutrients, making it effortless to apply the right dosage to each tree. All I have to do is insert the spikes into the ground around the drip line of the trees and let them work their magic. Theres no need for mixing or measuring, and the spikes are easy to handle and store. Its a hassle-free approach that even beginners can handle with ease.", "Ive noticed a significant improvement in the health and appearance of my evergreen trees since I started using Jobes Fertilizer Spikes. The cypress, juniper, and magnolia trees have all shown vigorous growth and lush green foliage. The spikes have helped them withstand environmental stressors, such as drought and harsh weather conditions, ensuring they remain resilient throughout the year. Its truly a testament to the effectiveness of Jobes Fertilizer Spikes.", "Furthermore, Jobes Fertilizer Spikes are tailored to meet the specific needs of evergreen trees like cypress, juniper, and magnolia. The carefully balanced blend of nutrients addresses their unique requirements, providing a comprehensive solution for optimal growth and development. Whether its promoting root development, enhancing nutrient uptake, or stimulating overall tree health, Jobes Fertilizer Spikes cover all the essential aspects.", "I appreciate the longevity of Jobes Fertilizer Spikes. With a pack of 15 spikes, I have enough to last me for an entire season, ensuring my trees receive consistent nourishment. The spikes slowly dissolve over time, requiring fewer applications compared to liquid fertilizers or granular products. This not only saves me money but also reduces the environmental impact associated with frequent fertilization.", "In terms of helpfulness tips, I recommend following the instructions provided by Jobes for the best results. Make sure to insert the spikes at the recommended distance from the tree trunk and water the area thoroughly after application. Additionally, its advisable to apply the spikes during the trees active growing season to maximize nutrient absorption.", "In conclusion, Jobes Fertilizer Spikes for evergreen trees have revolutionized the way I care for my cypress, juniper, and magnolia trees. The slow release formula, convenience, and tailored nutrient blend have made a remarkable difference in the health and appearance of my trees. With their outstanding performance, ease of use, and long-lasting effects, Jobes Fertilizer Spikes are the ultimate solution for any gardener looking to achieve thriving evergreen trees. I wholeheartedly recommend Jobes Fertilizer Spikes for all evergreen tree enthusiasts."

Review text: I have been using AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients for several months now, and I am extremely pleased with the results. These nutrients have proven to be an essential component in the success of my indoor gardening endeavors., One of the standout features of AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients is their convenience. The pre-mixed formula eliminates the need for measuring and mixing different nutrients, saving me time and effort. The nutrients come in a concentrated form, allowing for easy and precise dosing. All I need to do is add the recommended amount to my AeroGarden system, and it takes care of the rest., The nutrient blend provided by AeroGarden is specifically formulated to meet the needs of indoor plants. It contains a balanced mix of essential elements, including nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium, as well as a variety of micronutrients. This comprehensive blend ensures that my plants receive all the necessary nutrients for healthy growth and development., I have noticed a significant improvement in the overall health and vitality of my plants since using AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients. The plants have grown more vigorously, with lush green foliage and vibrant flowers. The nutrients have also helped to promote robust root development, which is crucial for the overall well-being of the plants., Another aspect that I appreciate about AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients is their long-lasting effectiveness. This not only saves me money but also reduces the hassle of frequently purchasing and restocking nutrients., The packaging of the nutrients is well-designed, with a secure cap that prevents leaks and spills. The bottle is also labeled with clear instructions for dosage, making it easy for beginners to use. Additionally, AeroGarden provides comprehensive guidelines and information on nutrient requirements for different plant varieties, helping me make informed decisions about my gardening endeavors., One minor drawback is that AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients have a distinctive smell, which some users may find slightly unpleasant. However, once diluted and added to the AeroGarden system, the odor dissipates quickly, and it does not affect the overall indoor environment., "In conclusion, I highly recommend AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients to anyone growing plants indoors, particularly those using an AeroGarden system. The convenience, effectiveness, and balanced nutrient blend make it an excellent choice for promoting healthy and thriving plants. With AeroGarden Liquid Nutrients, I have witnessed significant improvements in plant growth, foliage quality, and flower production. It is an essential component of my indoor gardening routine, and I wouldnt hesitate to purchase it again."

Review text:
The manufacturer recommends 1-2 teaspoon per gallon for general purpose use.

I measured 1 teaspoon per gallon of MicroFlora to be ~300 PPM.

This is ~128

PPM of nitrates and ~136 PPM of calcium.

This is a really high dose of nitrate nitrogen that may hinder your bloom cycle.

If I were to use this product in grow cycle, I would only use 1/2 teaspoon per gallon, and 1/4 teaspoon per gallon in early bloom, and 1/8 teaspoon per gallon in late bloom.

Review text: "Im experimenting with some hydroponics now and needed a way to check the pH and then, of course, adjust if necessary.  I had purchased an inexpensive pH meter, but found that it was too large to use with the indoor gardens such as Aerogarden.  It wont fit into the water fill hole.  I started using these test solution with this group and found that its easier to use, and for my purposes, as long as its in a pretty wide range, the plants grow just fine.  I dont need to know within a tenth of a point what the pH is ... I just look to make sure its in the yellow-green area and I think its fine.  The Up and Down solutions work great.  Some of the fertilizers that I use do cause the pH to rise or fall below that range and a few drops of the Up or Down solution gets everything back in sync.  An additional benefit of the testing solution is that theres no calibration needed from time to time.  Reading reviews of even the more expensive pH meters people still complain about the calibration and some need to be stored in a solution ... just more trouble than Im willing to put up with for what I need."
